Assignment 14: Twitters Mining with rtweet

How to do it?:

  • Open the Rmarkdown file of this assignment (link) in Rstudio.

  • Right under each question, insert a code chunk (you can use the hotkey Ctrl + Alt + I to add a code chunk) and code the solution for the question.

  • Knit the rmarkdown file (hotkey: Ctrl + Alt + K) to export an html.

  • Publish the html file to your Githiub Page.

Submission: Submit the link on Github of the assignment to Canvas

  1. Pick a keyword or hashtag. Download the data associated with the keyword/hashtag. Plot at least 10 plots to visualize the data associated with the keyword/hashtag. All plots should have titles and captions.
keyword_search = 'United_States'

df <- search_tweets(q = keyword_search, 
                        n = 18000,
                        include_rts = FALSE,
                        `-filter` = "replies",
                        lang = "en") %>% 
  mutate(created_at = ymd_hms(format(created_at, tz = "US/Eastern")))

write_csv(df, 'twitter_data_america.csv')

df %>% 
  unnest_tokens(output = hashtag, input = text, token = "tweets") %>%
  filter(!hashtag %in% c("United_States",'America','infrastructure','bill'), str_detect(hashtag, "^#")) %>%
  count(hashtag, sort = TRUE) %>%
  head(5) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = n, y = reorder(hashtag, n)))+
  geom_col()+
  labs(x='Frequency', 
       y = 'Keyword', 
       title = 'Frequency of words on Twitter by Keywords', 
       caption = 'The keyword #america is most common on my twitter timeline.')

library(RColorBrewer)

pal <- brewer.pal(8,"Dark2")
library(wordcloud) 

df %>% 
  unnest_tokens(output = hashtag, input = text, token = "tweets") %>%
  filter(!hashtag %in% c("United_States",'America','infrastructure','bill'), str_detect(hashtag, "^#")) %>%
  count(hashtag, sort = TRUE) %>%
  mutate(hashtag = str_remove(hashtag, '#')) %>% 
  filter(hashtag != 'bill') %>% 
  with(wordcloud(hashtag, n, random.order = FALSE, max.words = 50, colors = pal))

  1. Choose a location then pick a trending keyword/hashtag in the location. Download the data associated with the keyword/hashtag. Plot at least 10 plots to visualize the data associated with the keyword/hashtag. All plots should have titles and captions.

Plot 1:

df %>% 
  filter(!is.na(location), !location=='United_States') %>% 
  count(location, sort = TRUE) %>%
  head(5) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = n, y = reorder(location, n)))+
  geom_col()+
   labs(x='Frequency', 
       y = 'Place', 
       title = 'Place of Origin for Tweets on my timeline', 
       caption = 'The United States is the most common country that tweets come from on my timeline.')

Plot 2:

words <- df %>%
  mutate(text = str_remove_all(text, "&amp;|&lt;|&gt;"),
         text = str_remove_all(text, "\\s?(f|ht)(tp)(s?)(://)([^\\.]*)[\\.|/](\\S*)"),
         text = str_remove_all(text, "[^\x01-\x7F]")) %>% 
  unnest_tokens(word, text, token = "tweets") %>%
  filter(!word %in% stop_words$word,
        !word %in% str_remove_all(stop_words$word, "'"),
        str_detect(word, "[a-z]"),
        !str_detect(word, "^#"),         
        !str_detect(word, "@\\S+"),
        !word %in% c('united_states','america')) %>%
  count(word, sort = TRUE)

al <- brewer.pal(8,"Dark2")
library(wordcloud) 
words %>% 
  with(wordcloud(word, n, random.order = FALSE, max.words = 50, colors = pal))

df %>% 
  unnest_tokens(output = word, input = text, token = "words") %>%
  anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% 
  filter(!word %in% c('https', 't.co')) %>% 
  count(word, sort = TRUE) %>%

Plot 5:

df %>% 
  select(screen_name, favourites_count) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(favourites_count)) %>% 
  group_by(screen_name) %>% 
  summarise(average_fav = mean(favourites_count)) %>% 
  arrange(-average_fav) %>% 
  head(10) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=average_fav, y = reorder(screen_name, average_fav)))+
  geom_col()+
  labs(y='Account')

Plot 6:

df %>%
    unnest_tokens(input = text, output = word) %>% 
    anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% 
    count(word, sort = TRUE) %>%
    inner_join(get_sentiments("nrc")) %>%
    filter(!is.na(sentiment)) %>%
    count(sentiment, sort = TRUE) %>% 
    mutate(n = n/sum(n)) %>% 
    ggplot(aes(y= reorder(sentiment, n), x = n))+geom_col()+
    labs(y='Relative Frequency', x ='')
